Income Classification¶

By Clint Greene¶

Introduction¶

The income dataset was collected by the U.S. Census Bureau. It contains weighted census data extracted from the 1994 and 1995 Current Population Surveys. Each line of the dataset contains 40 demographic and employment related variables as well as an instance weight for the observation and a label for each observation, which indicates whether the particular population component had an income of greater than or less than $50k. The dataset contains a total of 199,523 instances.

Objective¶

The goal is to predict whether a person makes over 50K a year or not given their demographic information. To achieve this, several machine learning algorithms are explored and the Light Gradient Boosted machine classifier gives the best performance.

Data Cleaning¶

Looking through the unique values per feature we can see that many features have missing values such as state of previous residence and major occupation code. Lets dive deeper and see just how many missing values exist in the samples. Here I will treat a sample as having a missing value if it contains '?', 'Do not know', 'Not in universe', or 'Not in universe or children'.

In [5]:
vals = []
cols = []
for col in data.columns:
    a = data.loc[data[col] == "?", col].size
    b = data.loc[data[col] == "Not in universe", col].size
    c = data.loc[data[col] == "Do not know", col].size
    d = data.loc[data[col] == "Not in universe or children", col].size
    e = data.loc[data[col] == "Not in universe under 1 year old", col].size
    if a or b or c or d or e:
        vals.append([a,b,c,d,e])
        cols.append(col)
missing = pd.DataFrame(np.array(vals).T, columns = cols, index=['?', 'Not in universe', 'Do not know', 'Not in universe or children', 'Not in universe under 1 year old'])

I decided to drop two additional categorical features: year and detailed household summary in household. Year was dropped because this attribute only signifies the year the census data that sample was collected and has no effect on income level. Detailed household summary in household was dropped because it is coarse and redudant version of detailed househould and family stat attribute. This reduces the feature space.

In [15]:
def pipeline(data, num_features, ohe=True, add_features=True):
    from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
    num_data = data.copy(deep=True)[num_features]
    
    if add_features:
        num_data['age2'] = num_data['age']**2
        num_data['edu2'] = num_data['edu_level']**2
        num_data['capital net'] = num_data['capital gains'] - num_data['capital losses']
        
        num_features = num_features + ['age2', 'edu2', 'capital net']
        
    cat_features = [name for name in data.columns if name not in num_features]
    cat_data = data.copy(deep=True)[cat_features]
    if ohe:
        encoder = OneHotEncoder(drop='first', sparse=False)
        cat_data = encoder.fit_transform(cat_data)
        cat_names = encoder.get_feature_names(cat_features)
        cat_data = pd.DataFrame(data=cat_data,columns=cat_names)
    else: encoder = None
        
    piped_data = pd.concat([num_data.reset_index(drop=True), cat_data.reset_index(drop=True)], axis=1)
    return piped_data, num_features, encoder
In [17]:

In [135]:
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedShuffleSplit
from prunedcv import PrunedGridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier

svmParams = {'penalty':['l1', 'l2'], 'alpha':np.logspace(-3, 3, 7)}
logParams = {'penalty':['l1', 'l2'], 'alpha':np.logspace(-3, 3, 7)}
forestParams = {'n_estimators':[100, 250, 500, 1000],'max_depth':[8, 16, 32, 64],
             'min_samples_split':[2, 5, 10, 25],'min_samples_leaf':[1, 2, 5, 10]}

svm = SGDClassifier(loss='hinge', class_weight='balanced', n_jobs=-1, early_stopping=True, n_iter_no_change=10, 
                    validation_fraction=0.15, random_state=rng)
log = SGDClassifier(loss='log', class_weight='balanced', n_jobs=-1, early_stopping=True, n_iter_no_change=10, 
                    validation_fraction=0.15, random_state=rng)
forest = RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced_subsample', n_jobs=-1, random_state=rng)

params = [svmParams, logParams, forestParams]                                                                          
models = [svm, log, forest]

sss_outer = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=5, test_size=0.4, random_state=rng)

cv = [[] for _ in range(len(models))]
for tr, ts in sss_outer.split(X_train,y_train):
    for i, (model, param) in enumerate(zip(models, params)):
        best_m = PrunedGridSearchCV(model, param, scoring='f1', cv=3, normalize=True)
        best_m.fit(X_train.iloc[tr], y_train.iloc[tr], sample_weight=iw_train.iloc[tr])
        sd = StandardScaler()
        sd.fit(X_train.iloc[tr])
        s = f1_score(y_train.iloc[ts], best_m.estimator.predict(sd.transform(X_train.iloc[ts])), sample_weight=iw_train.iloc[ts])
        cv[i].append((s,best_m.best_params))

cv = cv + new_cv

curMax = [-float('inf')]
for ii in range(len(cv)):
    curRes = cv[ii]
    curAvg = []
    for jj in range(len(curRes)):
        curAvg.append(curRes[jj][0])
        if curRes[jj][0] > curMax[0]:
            curMax = (curRes[jj][0],curRes[jj][1],clfs[ii])
    avg_scores.append(np.mean(curAvg))
print('Top performing classifier over all sets was a %s with an average score: %s' %(clfs[np.argmax(avg_scores)], np.max(avg_scores)))
print('Max score %s found by %s with params %s' %(curMax[0], curMax[2], curMax[1]))
